Hello,

We are trying to localize the text of some our features/tools in our activities and are running into issues where some labels aren't translated.

We have created a label bundle according to the following guidelines:

https://help.learnosity.com/hc/en-us/articles/360000758697-Internationalizing-and-Localizing-the-Assessment-Experience
https://reference.learnosity.com/questions-api/questions-api-i18n
https://reference.learnosity.com/assess-api/assess-api-i18n

We have confirmed that the label bundle is passed in our front end's Learnosity initialization. Our label bundle is included in the attachment, learnosity_init_request.json. 

We noticed that only some of the labels in the label bundle actually translate, namely:

1. Undo- Borrar
2. Redo - Repetir
3. Reset	- Reiniciar
4. Point - Punton
5. Line - Recta

All of these translations that have worked are part of the graphing plot question type. We found that the buttons for tools -- such as rulers and protractors -- still use English labels. 

We would like to know whether we are incorrectly initializing the Learnosity activity, misunderstood the API, or if there is an issue on the Learnosity side.

Thanks,
Chris

Hello, 

 We are trying to localize the text of some our features/tools in our activities and are running into issues where some labels aren't translated. 

 We have created a label bundle according to the following guidelines: 

 https://help.learnosity.com/hc/en-us/articles/360000758697-Internationalizing-and-Localizing-the-Assessment-Experience

https://reference.learnosity.com/questions-api/questions-api-i18n

https://reference.learnosity.com/assess-api/assess-api-i18n 

 We have confirmed that the label bundle is passed in our front end's Learnosity initialization. Our label bundle is included in the attachment, learnosity_init_request.json.  

 We noticed that only some of the labels in the label bundle actually translate, namely: 

 1. Undo- Borrar

2. Redo - Repetir

3. Reset	- Reiniciar

4. Point - Punton

5. Line - Recta 

 All of these translations that have worked are part of the graphing plot question type. We found that the buttons for tools -- such as rulers and protractors -- still use English labels.  

 We would like to know whether we are incorrectly initializing the Learnosity activity, misunderstood the API, or if there is an issue on the Learnosity side. 

 Thanks,

Chris

Hi Chris,

We are looking into this and one of our team will be back with more information.

Kind Regards,
Learnosity Support Team

Hi Chris,

Is it only the following labels that are not translating for you?
  "calculator": "Calculadora",   "protractor": "Transportador",  "ruler": "Regla"
  
If that is the case I suspect the issue here is that you are trying to translate the wrong label.
As you can see in the documentation, we have Assess API labels and Questions API labels. Calculator, Protractor, and Ruler exist as different entities in both.

 "labelBundle": {
      "questionsApiLabelBundle": {
        "graphingTools": {
          "move": "Mover",
          "point": "Punto",
          "segment": "Segmento",
          "line": "Recta",
          "ray": "Semirrecta",
          "polygon": "Polígono"
        },
        "redo": "Repetir",
        "undo": "Borrar",
        "reset": "Reiniciar"
      },
      "calculator": "Calculadora",
      "protractor": "Transportador",
      "ruler": "Regla"
    }
 
From your request above I can see that you are translating these outside of the "questionsApiLabelBundle" object. Therefore it is translating the 'Calculator' button in the player. For example:

​​


If you want to translate the button for the calculator feature, you would need to add this inside the questionsApiLabelBundle object.

​​

Does that make sense?

Let me know if that solves the issue.

Thanks,
Conor

Hi Connor, that makes sense, thanks. We can give that a try and get back to you. 

 I guess we missed calculator in the Question API, although ruler and protractor do not seem to be listed in the docs for the question api label bundle

Hi Chris,

You're right, it's not in the docs and doesn't seem to translate.
Apologies, I only tested using calculator.

Let me check again, and I'll come back with more information shortly.

Thanks,
Conor

Thanks Conor - can you please also add Chris Valcourt to this ticket? cvalcourt@cainc.com. 

 Thanks,

Lauren

No problem Lauren. Chris Valcourt is now added.

Cheers,
Conor

Hi Chris,

Apologies for the mistake in my first message. Only calculator exists in both the Assess API and Questions API. I should have tested all three before replying.

So after more investigation, I can now see that the label for the Protractor and Ruler are set by the author.

​​

This label is not translated using the labelBundle. Instead, the author must translate this label.

I hope that helps.

Thanks,
Conor

Original ticket raised by Erik Vinicius at Schoology

Issue
provide asset urls/information in the student response for audio and video recording

Priority context
Low to Medium 

Client Context
Medium

We provide item level performance reports and we have the answer listed as one of the columns. Given this couldn't be represented as text, the closest seems to be a link to the resource. It wouldn't need to be a direct link to download it, if there's an endpoint in data api for example we could have an endpoint of our own that would properly auth and redirect to resource.


Detailed Feature Description
As a client developer, I want to get the asset links (actual path, not relative links) of video or audio recording of the student's response so that I am able to use those for my own implementation.
As a client developer, I want to get more information stored of the audio recording of the student's response, similar to what's available in the video recording response, so that I am able to use those for my own implementation.

e.g. audio only has location,type,length while video has name,originalName,extension,size,assetPath,assetProcessedPath,duration,webType

I'll wait for the long term solution then.

Clarification
Sorry, I wasn't asking about why you use inline or asses. I was asking when/why you use author-defined activities versus a dynamic items array in the in-page request object.

If an activity with items has been predefined, you only need to use the activity_template_id, not the items array. If you want to define the items array in the in-page request object (for example, if you want to pick the items at random or by some other programmatic means) you don't need to predefine an activity.

10005 and display error

The reason you saw response not found errors is as you surmised. The response_ids are different than expected because the first time you initialized the assessment you used object syntax (possibly created by the Author API), and the second time you initialized it, you used linear strings.

This is also why your content didn't display without the items array, and didn't display responses with the items array. You shouldn't need to provide an array on top of the activity definition, which I'll discuss further below. But to show you what happens, if you use the activity object syntax array, and don't provide the items array, we expect to see a span for inline that uses the id in the object syntax. 

When you build your own object syntax, that's typically the same and it's a non-issue. But, because the Author API is UI-driven, and must support multiple item banks, it must account for the possibility that two items in different banks might have the same reference. So it creates a unique ID each time.

So, if you must change a pre-defined activity to inline rendering, what you would have to do this (using your example):
 {
    "rendering_type" => "inline",
    "type" => "submit_practice",
    "state" => "review",
    "name" => "CHC_of Grade 6 Module 1 Topic A Quiz",
    "user_id" => "166d57ea-3d1d-46a2-a3d7-ce372de10cc6",
    "session_id" => "7a699660-c89b-482f-8758-13ce6ea57bac",
    "activity_id" => "d0e4e124-7a1d-4823-ae6c-34369cf94aad",
    "activity_template_id" => "31f2b6ba-b866-47d8-acb2-a787dd3d46d5"
}  <span class="learnosity-item" data-reference="d0ef838e-ce29-4e55-9bb8-cdf15e4ff3da"></span>
<span class="learnosity-item" data-reference="16f6869d-7d51-4f2a-b7ab-27e04e7f4cad"></span>
<span class="learnosity-item" data-reference="d3903737-5506-43b1-bcda-43097f340f3e"></span> 
That's not ideal, but it's a byproduct of a few things. The Author API must be able to support multiple item banks when creating activities, so it must use the object syntax. The issue you saw has never come up before because the typical use case with activities is to define the activity and initialize using the activity_template_id, without a duplicate items array, as above. In that case, the same object-syntax items array created by the Author API is used every time.

In your case, when you overrode the activity definition and provided your own items array of strings. The response_id generated becomes different. As a result, the responses stored using the original items array can't be found. That's why (when you provided the items array of strings) you saw the items appear, but the responses weren't there.

Resolution

On our side, we will look at what can be done for this edge case where the items array changes syntax between init and review. I'll quote a bit from a prior post to collect it here for convenience:
  We've found an issue on our side that's responsible for the 10005: Response not found error. It's related to your observations, and how you initialize, whether and when you use an array of strings or an array of objects.

We may also play a part in this through some sort of validation, but we need to escalate to the engineers for discussion. Customers can currently adapt that syntax based on which item banks they want to use. So, we're not sure if this is a bug, based both on use case, or perhaps a feature that standardizes init, and how we handle existing customer code without introducing breaking changes. 
  
On your side, the best way to resolve this is for us to better understand your workflow, why you're using both activity definition and dynamic items array simultaneously and, if this is required for your workflow, how to do so to avoid this error.

Thanks,
Rich

Hi Javier,

To answer your prior post:

Regarding the diagram, I see a couple of possible clarity issues, and I'm not sure what you mean by changing the item order--specifically, where that fits in. I think it would be simpler to describe when this issue occurs.

The problem exists when trying to resume or review when the item reference and possible item id in the items array don't match. So here are the simple scenarios:

1) Init and resume/review with array of strings: Success
"items":["item1", "item2"]

2) init and resume/review with array of objects: Success
"items":[ {"id":"item1", "reference":"item1"}, {"id":"item1", "reference":"item1"} ]

3) init with object syntax where id and reference match, and resume with string syntax, or vice versa: Success.
"items":[ {"id":"item1", "reference":"item1"}, {"id":"item1", "reference":"item1"} ]
"items":["item1", "item2"]
or
"items":["item1", "item2"]
"items":[ {"id":"item1", "reference":"item1"}, {"id":"item1", "reference":"item1"} ]

4) init with object syntax where id and reference don't match, and resume with string syntax, or vice versa: Failure.
"items":[ {"id":"093482038", "reference":"item1"}, {"id":"490586048", "reference":"item1"} ]
"items":["item1", "item2"]
or
"items":["item1", "item2"]
"items":[ {"id":"093482038", "reference":"item1"}, {"id":"490586048", "reference":"item1"} ]

This fails by not finding the responses when resuming or reviewiing.

When you control the items array, this is not an issue. But when your authors just add items using the Author API UI, and your devs later resume with strings, neither are aware that the original activity was created with randomly generated uuids for each item id. This is is necessary because every entry in the array must be unique and the Author API can't predict if the same reference may appear more than once across all applicable item banks.

Similarly, if you intend to switch from assess to inline rendering when resuming or reviewing, you'll need to use the id when activities are originated with the Author API, not reference.

Put simply, if you always initialize the same way, you won't have a problem. 

Does that make sense?
Rich

You would be well aware of the other case where this could occur, because it would be you specifying the items array in object syntax yourself, if ever. The only reason you would need to do that is if you knowingly wanted to duplicate an item in the same session (which, again, is the reason the Author API takes this approach).

I've been thinking about this a lot today, and we've been discussing how we could make this more transparent. One possible idea was to only use the id when a known conflict (repetition of the same item) was found. Or always make the id match the item reference unless a conflict was found, which would have the same effect. In both cases, we might alert the author during activity building. This would eliminate this case 90% of the time and alert the other 10%. This is just one idea, and is a future development effort.

It would help us a lot to understand why, when, and how you run into this. Would you mind elaborating just a bit:

1) Why do you switch from assess to inline rendering?

2) When you initialize, how do you know what you need for the init packet? That is, an author creates the activity and then you, the developer, initialize. What do you know/have you stored at that time? You must know the activity_template_id. But how did you get the list of items when you initialized and ran into this issue the first time and opened the ticket? Do you also store the items array along with the activity_template_id? Do you look it up using the Data API? Or did you just run into this by going through the motions manually because you're just building/testing this workflow?

Thanks,
Rich

 In a glance instead of exposing the item bank item id (you could still use it internally, so that there are no big changes at your BE) we could initialize the inline/assess items using the organisation_id when necessary, it is likely your clients are already using it and they have information. 

One thing I am assuming is that the item reference is unique inside an item bank, I think it is.

 {

   items: ['GREA_10', 'GREA_11]

} 

 Here users just need to pass the references, you guys can assume the user is trying to load the items from the default item bank. 

 2. With organisation_id 

 {

   organisation_id: 503,

   items: ['GREA_10', 'GREA_11]

} 

 Similar than before just that instead of using the default item bank it will use the provided one. 

 3. With multiple organisation_id

{

   organisation_id: 503,

   items: ['GREA_10', { reference: 'GREA_11', organisation_id: 498}]

} 

 In this we are passing at the item level the item bank id, so I can tell Learnosity that I am expecting to load that item from the provided item bank, for those items with no the organisation_id we can default to the root value or the default, or just force people to always pass the organisation_id at the item level in this case. 

 The advantage that I see is that you don't need to expose the item bank item id  and you can resolve it based on the reference and the provided organisation_id

subject: Feature request: storing all the student responses by default rather than us using the metadata

comments.body:
Raised from https://learnositysupport.zendesk.com/agent/tickets/12249

We allow the user to attempt a question multiple times which is functionality the default API provides. We need to be able to record every attempt the student makes. Learnosity only records the most recent attempt so we use the metadata to store the information. We also had issues around questions backed by a data table so we store that data in the question response metadata.

As a feature request would it be possible to store all the student responses by default rather than us using the metadata?

Raised from https://learnositysupport.zendesk.com/agent/tickets/12249

We allow the user to attempt a question multiple times which is functionality the default API provides. We need to be able to record every attempt the student makes. Learnosity only records the most recent attempt so we use the metadata to store the information. We also had issues around questions backed by a data table so we store that data in the question response metadata.

As a feature request would it be possible to store all the student responses by default rather than us using the metadata?


  Kind Regards,

Dmitry Kochnev

Original ticket raised by Justin Ball at Atomic Jolt

Issue
Learnosity does not save all students' responses (attempts) for the question.

Priority context
Medium

Client Context
[AJ]
We allow the user to attempt a question multiple times which is functionality the default API provides. We need to be able to record every attempt the student makes. Learnosity only records the most recent attempt so we use the metadata to store the information. We also had issues around questions backed by a data table so we store that data in the question response metadata.

AJ is using https://reference.learnosity.com/items-api/methods#question-Response.setMetadata to save different responses from Student (if session was resumed and response changed). AJ analyses the best attempt even if the last one stored at Learnosity is incorrect, student can get bonuses as answered better sometimes.

As a feature request would it be possible to store all the student responses by default rather than us using the metadata?

Detailed Feature Description
This is a very custom request from AJ and I do not remember anything like this from other clients. 
Api should be able to save different responses (attempts) from student for particular session / response as a standard field in api (so clients do not have to use metadata fields for that).

Hi Justin,

I raised that feature request just for storing and no further consideration in terms of reporting / scoring / etc.

Will keep you posted on any news here.


  Kind Regards,

Dmitry Kochnev

[JIRA->ZD Notification]

Feature Request FEAT-616 has not been approved for development. Please see jira ticket for further details and contact the Sydney office if you have any concerns

Hi Justin,

This has also not been picked up for development within the near future so please continue with the current implementation in the metadata. 


  Kind Regards,

Learnosity Support Team

       }]
 }
 
I'm not sure how the correct answer was set to include only labels. Perhaps the json source of the question was edited, or it was created using the Data API.
So I would like to find out if this only started causing an error recently?


  I do not think the assignment can be changed mid-assessment, after all the students have already gone through it, without removing all of the students work.  If you simply set the correct answer in the graphing question in Item "A695-3ZLA_I_550255", this will not remove past student's responses.
By setting a correct answer to this question now, it will overwrite the incorrect validation, and you will no longer see the error when reviewing student's responses.
If you remove the question or Item, or change the question type, or change the item references, this will affect the student's responses and will cause an error. However, by simply adding a correct answer to the question using the Author Site for example, this will not affect student responses.

However, one thing to note, if the correct answer was incorrect all along, then the students were not getting the correct score for that item. Their score will not be updated automatically once you set the correct answer.
To update their score, you will need to change the score manually using the Data API's Update Response Scores endpoint.
Do you think the students have been receiving an incorrect score for this item all along?

I hope that makes sense. Please let me know if you have any questions.

Thanks,
Conor

subject: Rate Limit increase for set itembank necessary

comments.body: the rate limit for set item is blocking our ability to provide a rescoring capability for our users. we need this limit to increase.
the rate limit for set item is blocking our ability to provide a rescoring capability for our users. we need this limit to increase.

Hi Joe,

We'll escalate this to Customer Success and someone will get back to you as soon as possible.

Can you describe what set item has to do with rescoring so we understand your use case?

Thanks,
Rich

Hey Rich, 

 We can create resources that can be copied to multiple courses.  

 Due to our versioning system we didn't need to create new items against learnosity during the copy for if someone changed a question in a course it  we'd create a new item. So we treated the questions as immutable. 

 For rescoring, though, we need to go back to previous versions and change a question definition, so if a question was copied from a resource to a course, the change would reflect on other copies in other courses. 

 Because we're now creating new items for all copies from a resource, we saw the increase in the [SET] itembank/* calls.

Hi Erik,

I think I understand the context here now, but it's likely based on a possible confusion covered in this ticket.

Now that we have context, let's continue that discussion on that ticket.

For this ticket, we've seen from our analysis that the only limits you're hitting are set items and set questions and we now understand why. If the main reason for this is rescoring, this may no longer be an issue. However, I think the Customer Success department is talking to Product and Engineering about adjusting rate limits just for Schoology. I'll ping Chris Perdue who may know more about that.

Thanks,
Rich

This is a follow-up to your previous request #13066 "Request for Another Organization" 

 This is a follow-up to your previous request #13066 "Request for Another Organization" 

 Learnosity,

As we started down the path of coding against the new org, we noticed that this looks like a new item bank and not a new org, where the secret and key is the same, but a separate organisation_id(634 vs. 20) is now required in the requests.  We had a few questions about this:

- In the past, a new org meant new secret and keys, why was this created different from past new content orgs ?

- Are there any performance concerns if, for example, this new content is used more often than our existing content, if it's in the same org, but different item bank (please correct me if I'm misunderstanding the terms used, there was some confusion here)

- is there an option of converting this item bank to a separate content org and would that provide any benefit, aside from us not having to recode how we make requests.

We are in the process of scoping out the code changes required on our side now, any answers to these questions would prove useful to us.

Thanks!

Hi Chris,

From a vocabulary standpoint, "organization/org" andorganisation_id refer only to an item bank, where tags/questions/items/activities are stored. A "consumer" is where student submissions are stored and is the access point separate credentials.

For what you requested, a new item bank is required, and this is the strongly recommended workflow. This is critical for things like multi-item-bank access, the activity builder in the Author API, and analytics-Console-related needs.

- In the past, a new org meant new secret and keys, why was this created different from past new content orgs ? 
Sorry, you asked or another item bank so I may have misunderstood your needs. If you have a pressing need for segregated student submissions, which was not described in your original request, I can forward this request to Customer Success. Typically, customers. get three consumer/org pairs: prod, dev, and load testing. CA has seven consumers and six orgs (item banks). While it's a little easier to provision item banks, provisioning consumers has both logistical and cost ramifications that would need to be discussed.

- Are there any performance concerns if, for example, this new content is used more often than our existing content, if it's in the same org, but different item bank (please correct me if I'm misunderstanding the terms used, there was some confusion here)
No worries. Org = item bank, Consumer = student submission database and credentials. There are no performance issues with using organisation_id rather than a separate consumer. The reverse is true because there is no additional authentication step for every request to the additional org. Orgs can be linked to multiple consumers.

- is there an option of converting this item bank to a separate content org and would that provide any benefit, aside from us not having to recode how we make requests.
This likely doesn't warrant a new consumer, but that's an issue for Customer Success, and I'll bring this to their attention. In any case, as I mentioned in the first question above, use of organization_id is the standard, is highly recommended, and has multiple benefits over separate consumers. If you ever use the Author API, you can build an activity from multiple item banks with one initialization of the API. When using the Items API, you can build assessments from multiple item banks using organisation_id, and analytics on these assessments can be returned using the Reports API. 

Let us know if you have more questions,
Rich

Thanks Rich, this is helpful.  We'll discuss internally and let you know if we need any changes.  Based on your response, performance does not seem to be a concern and we will most likely leave it as is.

In the Learnosity question editor for a True/False question, the Simple Features modal has a max height set when there is nothing loaded in the RTE, which creates a scrolling problem for the modal footer. Once a tool/feature has been loaded into the RTE, the max height is removed and the modal behaves as expected.
The other question types do not have this max height set. Is there a reason for the max height? Can this be removed?

In the Learnosity question editor for a True/False question, the Simple Features modal has a max height set when there is nothing loaded in the RTE, which creates a scrolling problem for the modal footer. Once a tool/feature has been loaded into the RTE, the max height is removed and the modal behaves as expected.

The other question types do not have this max height set. Is there a reason for the max height? Can this be removed?

Hi Brittani,

Can you please clarify a couple of things? 

What do you mean by 'when there is nothing loaded/once a tool/feature has been loaded in the RTE'? I can't think of what could load into the RTE, and don't see that in your video.

Can you please describe what the problem is in the video? Perhaps with a timecode or screenshot? We don't see an issue related to height so we're probably missing something and want to understand the problem. Is there a before and after shot that shows the height problem and then when it's fixed?

Can you take a screenshot of how TF treats this modal differently than any other question types? I just tried, for example, TF and Cloze with Drag and Drop and don't see a difference.

Thanks,
Rich

Sure thing. Maybe "loaded" isn't the correct term. I provided two screenshots, one with the correct view of the modal where you can clearly see the Cancel and OK buttons in the footer. In the other screenshot, the buttons aren't visible, and the user has to scroll down in the modal to see the buttons. You can also see the highlighted element in the console, showing there's a max-height set of 489px. If this max height is removed, the modal adjusts to the correct height to show the buttons.  

 In the video, you can see the user clicks the Tools button and the modal appears, then scrolls down and clicks "OK" to add the Audio Player. In the text box, you now see the "Bar audio player". This is what I mean by "a feature is loaded into the RTE". When the user clicks the Tools button again, the modal behaves correctly and shows the Cancel and OK buttons. Not shown in the video: if you remove the "Bar audio player" from the RTE, and click Tools again, the modal has the max height set again. 

 I added another video with a multiple choice question showing the correct modal behavior. You'll notice when the modal is opened, it adjusts to the correct height as it loads, and the buttons remain visible.
To simplify: the problem is the user has to scroll to see the Cancel and OK buttons because the modal is set at a max height, and not adjusting to the height of the content.

Hi Brittani,

Okay, we can't reproduce this so we're now looking into whether the Question Editor behaves differently when embedded on its own, versus inside the Author API, and whether different version may behave differently. 

Can you tell us which version of the Question Editor you're using in your screenshots/video?

Thanks,
Rich

-- Horacio

subject: Activity is submitted before time limit has expired

comments.body:
We keep getting reports of exams that are being force submitted while students are taking them before the time limit is up. Today UWM reported a student with an exam of a time limit of 120 minutes cut short by about 15 minutes. The student's session id is e906079d-3dc0-4fec-a869-b1da617e571e and the consumer key is uJHK4HjSyvao7pjH

Here's the code that we have in place when a time limit is set. We set the limit_type to "hard" and give it a "max_time" of minutes * 60 to convert to seconds.

if override.time_limit
      init_options[:config][:time][:countdown_option] = true
      init_options[:config][:time][:limit_type] = "hard"
      init_options[:config][:time][:max_time] = override.time_limit * 60
    end

We record the event in our system as well and can see the student started at:
Tue, 05 May 2020 18:03:19 UTC +00:00

And the system force completed it at:
Tue, 05 May 2020 19:25:38 UTC +00:00

Do you know why it would be submitting before their time is up?

Are you sure that's the right session_id? If I understand your comment, you want to know why a session set for a hard limit of 120 minutes is submitting after approximately 105 minutes. 

However, that session shows a duration of 3 minutes, with the following started and completed times, and none of the questions are attempted.

            "dt_saved": "2020-05-05T18:06:30Z",
            "dt_started": "2020-05-05T18:03:12Z",
            "dt_completed": "2020-05-05T18:06:30Z",

Have I used the wrong data?

Rich

Sorry, wrong session id. Correct one is: 2d7e3266-e227-4da0-b1ee-9c7e07f24f33 

 We recorded started at 

Tue, 05 May 2020 18:08:38 UTC +00:00 

 and finished at

Tue, 05 May 2020 19:53:20 UTC +00:00

Rich Shupe​ not showing anything suspicious here - I think we need AJ to see if they can reproduce, and if so, capture the HAR file to get the init JSON for this activity - not so sure their override.time_limit is set correctly?

Gonzalo Zawadzki​ FYI
I saw somewhere that the hard limit value matched 120 minutes... 7200 I think? But it might have been been custom metadata, not a proper init value. Will check.

HI Justin,

We've been unable to reproduce and don't capture data that shows if a session was force submitted by a hard time limit. 

Can you reproduce? If so, can you capture a HAR file when successful?

Thanks,
Rich

I'll see what we can do. This was submitted by a student and so all we have to go off of is the data recorded in our db and in the session. We're going to work on figuring out how to replicate the issue.

Hello James, 

We are currently experiencing issues affecting the shared author site in all regions, preventing login. Our Systems Engineering teams are actively investigating the issue.

You can see the status on this page: https://status.learnosity.com/

And we'll keep you updated as soon as possible here on this ticket.

Thank you

Kind regards,
Angel

Hi James,

As of 3:30 UTC, access to authoring remains fully operational. Learnosity Support and Systems Engineering teams are continuing to monitor the issue, and will follow on with an update and resolution as soon as possible.

Please let me know if you're having any further issue.

Thank you

Kind regards,
Angel
Thank you so much for the update and the fix. It looks great!

subject: Location of API Server for Pearson HK

Hi support,

Could you please advise what is our current "API server" location? Has it been migrated to Australia AWS as agreed by Ben (refer to the attachment)? 

If not yet , could you please share the schedule with us?

Hi support, 

 Could you please advise what is our current "API server" location? Has it been migrated to Australia AWS as agreed by Ben (refer to the attachment)?  

 If not yet , could you please share the schedule with us?

Hi Erik,

The Pearson HK consumer uses the AU (Australian) region. And I believe it was set up this way from the beginning, so there was no need to be migrated.

Also, just to note, the following article might be helpful for you. It shows the endpoints that you should be using for each region for most efficiency. So you should be using the AU - Sydney endpoints in your application.
https://help.learnosity.com/hc/en-us/articles/360000754798-What-Regions-and-Endpoints-Should-I-Use-

Let me know if you have any questions.

Thanks,
Conor

Hi Conor, 

 Noted and thanks for your prompt reply. 

 Thanks & regards, 

 Erik
